To implement a hamburger menu for mobile devices, you need to update your theme's CSS and JavaScript, as well as make some adjustments to the header structure. Here is how you can enhance the menu:

1. **CSS for Hamburger Menu**: Update `style.css` to include styles for the hamburger icon and dropdown menu for mobile screens.
2. **JavaScript for Menu Toggle**: Add JavaScript to handle the visibility of the dropdown menu when the hamburger icon is clicked.
3. **Update `header.php`**: Modify the header structure to include a hamburger icon that only shows up on mobile.

### 1. Update `style.css`

Add the following styles for the hamburger icon and the mobile dropdown menu:

```css
/* Hamburger Menu Styles */
.hamburger {
    display: none;
    flex-direction: column;
    cursor: pointer;
    margin-left: auto;
}

.hamburger span {
    background: var(--header-text-white);
    height: 3px;
    width: 25px;
    margin: 4px;
    transition: all 0.3s ease;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .hamburger {
        display: flex;
    }

    nav {
        display: none;
        width: 100%;
    }

    nav ul {
        flex-direction: column;
        background-color: var(--header-bg);
        width: 100%;
        text-align: left;
    }

    nav.active {
        display: block;
    }

    nav ul li {
        width: 100%;
    }

    nav ul li a {
        padding: 15px;
    }

    header {
        flex-direction: row;
        align-items: center;
    }
}
```

### 2. Add JavaScript for Toggle Functionality

Add JavaScript to handle the dropdown visibility when the hamburger icon is clicked. You can enqueue a JavaScript file or add an inline script in `functions.php`.

Add the following JavaScript snippet:

```php
function my_custom_theme_enqueue_scripts() {
    // Enqueue main stylesheet
    wp_enqueue_style( 'my-custom-theme-style', get_stylesheet_uri(), array(), wp_get_theme()->get( 'Version' ) );

    // Enqueue JavaScript for the mobile menu
    wp_enqueue_script( 'my-custom-theme-js', get_template_directory_uri() . '/js/main.js', array('jquery'), '1.0', true );
}
add_action( 'wp_enqueue_scripts', 'my_custom_theme_enqueue_scripts' );
```

Create a `main.js` file in your theme's `js` directory with the following content:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const hamburger = document.querySelector('.hamburger');
    const navMenu = document.querySelector('nav');

    hamburger.addEventListener('click', function() {
        navMenu.classList.toggle('active');
    });
});
```

### 3. Update `header.php`

Modify `header.php` to add a hamburger icon for mobile:

```php
<header>
    <div class="logo">
        <?php
        if ( has_custom_logo() ) {
            the_custom_logo();
        } else {
            echo '<a href="' . esc_url( home_url( '/' ) ) . '">' . get_bloginfo( 'name' ) . '</a>';
        }
        ?>
    </div>
    <div class="hamburger mobile-only">
        <span></span>
        <span></span>
        <span></span>
    </div>
    <nav class="desktop-only">
        <?php
        wp_nav_menu( array(
            'theme_location' => 'primary',
            'menu_id'        => 'primary-menu',
            'container'      => false,
            'depth'          => 2, // Allows dropdowns
            'fallback_cb'    => 'wp_page_menu',
            'menu_class'     => 'primary-menu'
        ) );
        ?>
    </nav>
</header>
```

### Summary

- **CSS Changes**: Updated to style the hamburger icon and menu for mobile.
- **JavaScript**: Added a script to handle showing/hiding the mobile menu.
- **`header.php`**: Modified to include the hamburger icon for mobile devices.

Now, on mobile devices, a hamburger icon will appear, and clicking it will toggle the visibility of the menu items. This ensures a better mobile-friendly user experience.

Do I still need the following codes in my @media (max-width: 768px) function?

    .desktop-only {
        display: none;
    }

    .mobile-only {
        display: block;
    }

No, you no longer need those specific styles (`.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only`) in your `@media (max-width: 768px)` section, as the new styles for the hamburger menu handle the display logic more effectively. The updated version already includes appropriate classes and JavaScript to show and hide elements based on screen size and user interactions.

Here’s what each of those styles was doing and why they can now be removed:

1. **`.desktop-only { display: none; }`**: 
   - This was used to hide elements meant for desktop screens when viewed on smaller screens. In the updated implementation, you already set up the hamburger and the menu (`nav`) visibility in a more dynamic way using JavaScript, which handles the toggling between desktop and mobile views.

2. **`.mobile-only { display: block; }`**:
   - This rule ensured that mobile-specific elements, such as the hamburger icon, were visible only on mobile devices. In the updated version, you use a different approach for the hamburger's visibility within the CSS (`display: flex` for `.hamburger` in the media query), so there is no need for a `.mobile-only` class to handle this anymore.

### What to Do Instead
In the updated implementation:

- The **hamburger menu** (`.hamburger`) is already set to `display: flex` within the `@media (max-width: 768px)` block, and it's hidden by default otherwise. This makes the `.mobile-only` class redundant.
- The **navigation menu** (`nav`) is hidden by default (`display: none`) for mobile and toggled with JavaScript (`nav.active { display: block; }`), so the `.desktop-only` class isn't needed anymore either.

### Revised `@media (max-width: 768px)` Section
You can simplify your media query like this:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    header {
        flex-direction: row;
        align-items: center;
    }

    .hamburger {
        display: flex;
    }

    nav {
        display: none;
        width: 100%;
    }

    nav.active {
        display: block;
    }

    nav ul {
        flex-direction: column;
        background-color: var(--header-bg);
        width: 100%;
        text-align: left;
    }

    nav ul li {
        width: 100%;
    }

    nav ul li a {
        padding: 15px;
    }

    .section {
        padding: 40px 10px;
    }
}
```

This updated version ensures that your mobile-specific elements, like the hamburger icon and dropdown menu, work well without the need for `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` classes.

To make the rest of your site mobile-responsive and display different content for desktop and mobile users, you can continue using conditional classes like `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` but apply them more strategically across different sections of your theme. Here’s how you can achieve a consistent mobile-responsive experience:

### 1. **Utilize CSS Classes (`.desktop-only`, `.mobile-only`)**
- You can continue to use `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` to selectively display elements depending on whether the user is on a desktop or mobile device.

Update your CSS to ensure these classes work well across your entire theme:

```css
/* Desktop-only Elements */
.desktop-only {
    display: block;
}

/* Mobile-only Elements */
.mobile-only {
    display: none;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
    /* Mobile-specific overrides */
    .desktop-only {
        display: none;
    }

    .mobile-only {
        display: block;
    }
}
```

### 2. **Adjust HTML in Template Files (e.g., `header.php`, `footer.php`, `front-page.php`)**
- Depending on the content you want to show, wrap elements in `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` classes.

For example, in `header.php`:

```php
<div class="desktop-only">
    <!-- Content for desktop users -->
    <p>Welcome to our desktop site!</p>
</div>

<div class="mobile-only">
    <!-- Content for mobile users -->
    <p>Welcome to our mobile site!</p>
</div>
```

Similarly, update the landing page (`front-page.php`) and footer (`footer.php`) to customize the content for different screen sizes.

### 3. **Use Conditional Logic in PHP for Mobile vs. Desktop**
- For even more control, use PHP to serve different content based on the device. There are several WordPress plugins and helper libraries like **Mobile Detect** that allow you to add server-side conditions.

First, add the Mobile Detect library to your theme:
1. Download the library from [Mobile Detect GitHub](https://github.com/serbanghita/Mobile-Detect).
2. Include it in your `functions.php`:

```php
require_once get_template_directory() . '/path/to/Mobile_Detect.php';

$detect = new Mobile_Detect();
```

Now, in your template files (`header.php`, `footer.php`, etc.), use conditional logic:

```php
<?php
$detect = new Mobile_Detect();

if ( $detect->isMobile() && !$detect->isTablet() ) {
    // Content for mobile devices
    echo '<div class="mobile-only-content">This is for mobile users only.</div>';
} else {
    // Content for desktop devices
    echo '<div class="desktop-only-content">This is for desktop users only.</div>';
}
?>
```

### 4. **Responsive Design for Sections (Landing Page, Footer, etc.)**
To make different sections of your site mobile-responsive:

- **Landing Page (`front-page.php`)**: Use `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` to conditionally display elements. Also, adjust the grid layout or remove non-essential elements for mobile users to enhance loading speed and usability.

- **Footer (`footer.php`)**: Show different footer widgets or information for mobile users. For example, reduce the number of columns in the footer to keep it more compact on mobile.

### 5. **JavaScript for Additional Control**
You can also use JavaScript for more dynamic control over the DOM based on the user's device or screen width:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    if (window.innerWidth <= 768) {
        document.querySelector('.desktop-only').style.display = 'none';
        document.querySelector('.mobile-only').style.display = 'block';
    } else {
        document.querySelector('.desktop-only').style.display = 'block';
        document.querySelector('.mobile-only').style.display = 'none';
    }
});
```

### Summary
- **Use `.desktop-only` and `.mobile-only` classes**: To show or hide elements conditionally across different parts of your site.
- **Include conditional PHP logic**: Use libraries like Mobile Detect to differentiate between mobile and desktop users server-side.
- **Update CSS and JavaScript accordingly**: Ensure responsiveness with the right styling and interaction behavior.

This setup will give you the flexibility to offer a custom experience based on whether users are browsing on desktop or mobile devices, ensuring a responsive and optimized user interface throughout your website.

Yes, it's definitely possible to have the dropdown menu appear directly below the hamburger icon when it's clicked, similar to the dropdown menus seen in software like MS Word. This behavior can be achieved by positioning the navigation (`nav`) element right below the hamburger icon using CSS and JavaScript.

### Key Steps:

1. **Update CSS** to ensure the dropdown positioning is correct.
2. **Modify JavaScript** to toggle the dropdown when clicking the hamburger.

Here’s how you can implement this:

### 1. Update CSS for Dropdown Positioning

Adjust the CSS to make sure the menu is properly positioned under the hamburger icon:

```css
/* Hamburger Menu Styles */
.hamburger {
    display: none;
    flex-direction: column;
    cursor: pointer;
    margin-left: auto;
}

.hamburger span {
    background: var(--header-text-white);
    height: 3px;
    width: 25px;
    margin: 4px;
    transition: all 0.3s ease;
}

/* Dropdown menu styling for mobile */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .hamburger {
        display: flex;
    }

    nav {
        display: none;
        position: absolute;  /* Position relative to the hamburger icon */
        top: 100%;  /* Align directly below the hamburger */
        right: 0;
        background-color: var(--header-bg);
        width: auto;
        z-index: 1000;
        box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    }

    nav ul {
        flex-direction: column;
        background-color: var(--header-bg);
        width: 200px;  /* Set a specific width for the dropdown */
        padding: 10px;
    }

    nav ul li {
        width: 100%;
    }

    nav ul li a {
        padding: 10px;
        color: var(--header-text-white);
        display: block;
        text-align: left;
    }

    nav.active {
        display: block;
